         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the (good?) acts held him off, but his heart strove him to go out of the city as it were. To the forest ... </seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Die Taten hielten ihn fern, sein Herz [aber] bemühte sich gleichsam, aus der Stadt herauszugehen.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">The deeds kept him away, [but] his heart laboured, as it were, to go out of the town.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>176</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Thereupon the king Mahāprabhāsa summoned Hastāṅkuśa [and] said to him: Bring (the elephant)!</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Darauf rief König Mahāprabhāsa den Hastāṅkuśa [und] sprach zu ihm.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">Thereupon, king Mahāprabhāsa summoned Hastāṅkuśa [and] said to him:</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>380</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... whichever test, [if] you carefully tamed it, bring this elephant to me, in order to ... </seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Whatever repetition you may have done, if it is well tamed, bring me that elephant, …  (cf 178–186)</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>708</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[Wenn] ... er sorgfältig gezähmt [ist], [so] bringe mir den Elefanten!</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">[If] ... it has been carefully tamed, bring the elephant to me!</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>389</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... I am going out into the forest with pleasure. Here then Hastāṅkuśa (brought the elephant) with white colored [skin] like the mountain.  </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... he did ... [and] he said to him: O lord, this elephant is very excellently tamed ...   </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the lord knows the time ... Thereupon the king Mahāprabhāsa having sat on the elephant (went) out of the city.    </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">In the [tune] vanapraveśa: This king leaves for the forest with a fourfold company, being excellent like the mountain,   </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">and like the moon together with its rays surrounded by the planets, thus he appeared together with the company of ministers.  </seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">W(ie der Mond) mit [seinen] Strahlen, von Planeten umgeben, so nahm er [scil. König Mahāprabhāsa] sich zu der Zeit (in bzw. mit) [seinem] Ministergef(olge) aus.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">L(ike to the moon) with [her] rays, surrounded by planets, just so he [i.e. king Mahāprabhāsa] appeared at that time (among OR with) his ret(inue) of ministers.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>289</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="remarks">Fragments <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-pkns34"/>, <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-pkns37"/> (including 38), <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-pkns144"/> and <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-pkns398"/> belong to the same manuscript. The fragment is the right part of a leaf including the right margin which is mostly preserved. The fragment is generally in good condition.</note><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment">The remnants of the ligature that precedes <hi>yāmornta</hi> are compatible with the restoration <hi>nta</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment">The complete name of the tune is Skt. <hi>vanapraveśa-</hi>; it is 4x14 syllables and the rhythm is 7/7.</note></p>
         </div>
